-reaching practical consequences, beyond the realm of political structures and academic theory. The book does not present a magic bullet to resolve debates around independence – this is not its purpose, and the text in fact demonstrates why there is no objectively optimal approach in any or all contexts. Instead, it seeks to shed light on aspects of these situations often overlooked in discussions around the fate of nations, and it addresses what the consequences of constitutional paradigm shifts might be for individuals. Constitutional culture is a complex web of interconnected understandings and behaviours, and the vibrations from shaking or cutting a fundamental strand will be felt throughout the structure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aConstitutional lawzQuébec (Province). 0aConstitutional lawzQuébec (Province). 0aConstitutional lawzScotland. 0aConstitutional lawzSpainzCatalonia. 0aSelf-determination, NationalzQuébec (Province). 0aSelf-determination, NationalzQuébec (Province). 0aSelf-determination, NationalzScotland. 0aSelf-determination, NationalzSpainzCatalonia. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aCatalonia.  aQuebec.  aScotland.  aSecessionism.  aSpain.  aUnited Kingdom.  abill of rights.  aconstitution.  aconstitutional culture.  aidentity.  aindependence.  ainterculturalism.  anationalism.  arights.  arule of law.1 aFeldman, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Helen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z